│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│     case Intrinsic::abs: {                                                                 │
│       // ...                                                                               │
│       if (ScalarType != VectorType)                                                        │
│         return None;                                                                       │
│       return isVectorizableIntrinsic(I, Scalars);                                          │
│     }                                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ This implies a different location. The analysis mentions                                   │
│ `BoUpSLP::getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall`. I now believe this function name is a red herring. │
│ The logic is what matters.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The analysis says "prevent the vectorizer from changing the bitwidth of the `llvm.abs`     │
│ operation".                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ The problem is that `isSafeToDeflate` is too optimistic for `llvm.abs`. It should return   │
│ `false`.                                                                                   │
│ If `isSafeToDeflate` returns `false`, the `trunc` will not be sunk. The vectorizer will    │
│ then have to vectorize `trunc(vectorized_abs_i64(...))`. This is correct.                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ So, one fix is to remove `Intrinsic::abs` from `isTriviallyVectorizable`.                  │
│ Let's check the impact. This would prevent sinking casts past `abs` in all cases. This     │
│ might be too restrictive if the cast is safe (e.g. `i32` to `i32`). But `isSafeToDeflate`  │
│ is for sinking a `trunc`, which by definition changes the type. So it's always from a      │
│ larger type to a smaller type. Sinking a `trunc` past an `abs` is exactly the bug.         │
│                                                                                            │
│ So, removing `Intrinsic::abs` from `isTriviallyVectorizable` seems correct.                │
│                                                                                            │
│ Let's find `isTriviallyVectorizable`.                                                      │
│ `grep250 -n 'isTriviallyVectorizable' 'llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp'`   │
│ I found its definition around line 800.                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp:800                                     │
│ static bool isTriviallyVectorizable(Intrinsic::ID ID) {                                    │
│   return ID == Intrinsic::sqrt || ID == Intrinsic::sin || ID == Intrinsic::cos ||          │
│          ID == Intrinsic::exp || ID == Intrinsic::exp2 || ID == Intrinsic::log ||          │
│          ID == Intrinsic::log10 || ID == Intrinsic::log2 ||                                │
│          ID == Intrinsic::fabs || ID == Intrinsic::floor ||                                │
│          ID == Intrinsic::ceil || ID == Intrinsic::trunc ||                                │
│          ID == Intrinsic::rint || ID == Intrinsic::nearbyint ||                            │
│          ID == Intrinsic::round || ID == Intrinsic::roundeven ||                           │
│          ID == Intrinsic::pow || ID == Intrinsic::fma || ID == Intrinsic::fmuladd ||       │
│          ID == Intrinsic::copysign || ID == Intrinsic::minnum ||                           │
│          ID == Intrinsic::maxnum || ID == Intrinsic::abs;                                  │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will remove `|| ID == Intrinsic::abs`.                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ However, the analysis also mentioned another fix location. Let's reconsider.               │
│ The analysis says: "The function `BoUpSLP::getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall` is responsible for │
│ deciding if a set of scalar intrinsic calls can be vectorized."                            │
│ And it proposes a fix in a `switch` statement.                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ I found `isSafeToDeflate` which has a `switch` on `I->getOpcode()`. For `CallInst`, it has │
│ another switch on `II->getIntrinsicID()`.                                                  │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // in isSafeToDeflate                                                                      │
│   case Instruction::Call: {                                                                │
│     auto *CI = cast<CallInst>(I);                                                          │
│     if (isTriviallyVectorizable(                                                           │
│             getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, /*TLI=*/nullptr)))                             │
│       return true;                                                                         │
│     if (auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(I)) {                                           │
│       switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {                                                      │
│       default:                                                                             │
│         return false;                                                                      │
│       case Intrinsic::smax:                                                                │
│       case Intrinsic::smin:                                                                │
│       case Intrinsic::umax:                                                                │
│       case Intrinsic::umin:                                                                │
│         return true;                                                                       │
│       }                                                                                    │
│     }                                                                                      │
│     return false;                                                                          │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ Instead of changing `isTriviallyVectorizable`, I could modify this `switch`.               │
│ If I add `case Intrinsic::abs: return false;` here, it would override the                  │
│ `isTriviallyVectorizable` check for `abs`. No, the `isTriviallyVectorizable` check comes   │
│ first.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ So I have two options:                                                                     │
│ 1. Remove `abs` from `isTriviallyVectorizable`. This is simple and seems correct.          │
│ 2. Modify `isSafeToDeflate` to special-case `abs`.                                         │
│    ```cpp                                                                                  │
│    case Instruction::Call: {                                                               │
│      auto *CI = cast<CallInst>(I);                                                         │
│      Intrinsic::ID ID = getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, /*TLI=*/nullptr);                  │
│      if (ID == Intrinsic::abs)                                                             │
│        return false;                                                                       │
│      if (isTriviallyVectorizable(ID))                                                      │
│        return true;                                                                        │
│      // ... rest of the function                                                           │
│    }                                                                                       │
│    ```                                                                                     │
│ This seems more targeted. It keeps `abs` as "trivially vectorizable" for other purposes,   │
│ but prevents cast deflation. This seems safer and more in line with the spirit of a        │
│ minimal fix.                                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ Let's check where else `isTriviallyVectorizable` is used.                                  │
│ `grep250 -n 'isTriviallyVectorizable' 'llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp'`   │
│ It's used in:                                                                              │
│ 1. `isSafeToDeflate` (which I'm looking at).                                               │
│ 2. `BoUpSLP::canVectorizeCall` - if an intrinsic is not trivially vectorizable, it checks  │
│ for a `VecFunc` in `VFDatabase`. `abs` should probably have a `VecFunc`.                   │
│ 3. `getSameOpcode` - if it's a call, it checks `isTriviallyVectorizable`. This is for      │
│ identifying similar instructions.                                                          │
│ 4. `BoUpSLP::getTreeEntry` - similar to `getSameOpcode`.                                   │
│ 5. `BoUpSLP::getInstructionCost` - for cost modeling.                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ If I remove `abs` from `isTriviallyVectorizable`, it might affect other parts of the       │
│ vectorizer, possibly pessimizing vectorization of `abs` in valid cases.                    │
│ So, the second option (modifying `isSafeToDeflate`) is better. It's more localized to the  │
│ problem of sinking casts.                                                                  │
